@node "MIDI" "What Is MIDI?"
@{b}@{u}What is MIDI?@{ub}@{uu}

MIDI is an acronym for Musical Instrument Digital Interface.  The  MIDI
language  is  a standard language which describes how to play a piece of
music. Most modern keyboard synthesizers come with this ability built in and
can  thus be used in a MIDI setup. Typically they can send out MIDI commands
describing what the keyboard player is playing or can interpret MIDI
commands sent  to  them  and play the corresponding music. Once a piece of
music is in MIDI form it can be manipulated  by  many  standard computer
programs.  For example, it could be played back at a different tempo,
transposed and even printed out in standard music notation.
@endnode

@node "MUI" "Magic User Interface (MUI)"
@{b}@{u}What is MUI?@{ub}@{uu}

MUI is a object-oriented interface builder on the @{"Amiga" link "Amiga" 0}. Programs that use
MUI usually have very eligant interfaces and are customizable to the user's
needs.

Some Amiga users don't like MUI because they say it is slow and uses up too
much memory. I, however, disagree and think this is part of progress. It
provides Amiga users with much much better interfaces than our poor friends
have on their @{"PCs" link "PC" 0}.
@endnode

