@node "NoteOn" "NoteOn MIDI message"
@{b}@{u}NoteOn message:@{ub}@{uu}

A NoteOn message is the message used in @{"MIDI" link "MIDI" 0} to indicate a note should be
played.
@endnode

@node "NoteOff" "NoteOff MIDI message"
@{b}@{u}NoteOff message:@{ub}@{uu}

A NoteOff message is the message used in @{"MIDI" link "MIDI" 0} to indicate a note should stop
playing.
@endnode

@node "SpectrumAnalyzer" "What is a spectrum analyzer?"
@{b}@{u}What is a spectrum analyzer?@{ub}@{uu}

A spectrum analyzer will show what frequencies are present in an audio
signal.
@endnode

@node "Oscilloscope" "oscilloscope"
@{b}@{u}What is an oscilloscope?@{ub}@{uu}

An oscilloscope allows you to see the waveform of a signal. This would allow
you to set the appropriate volume on your instrument to make sure it wasn't
too low or too high.
@endnode

@node "Tab" "What is tab?"
@{b}@{u}What is tab?@{ub}@{uu}

Tab (or tablature) is a method of writting down music specifically for
guitar. It says which fret and which string were used to play a note.
@endnode

@node "MIDIInterface" "What is a MIDI interface?"
@{b}@{u}What is a MIDI interface?@{ub}@{uu}

A MIDI interface is a standard set of connections which allow for @{"MIDI" link "MIDI" 0}
equipment to be linked together by cables.
@endnode

@node "Channels" "What are channels?"
@{b}@{u}What is a MIDI channel?@{ub}@{uu}

In @{"MIDI" link "MIDI" 0} there are 16 channels and messages can be sent over any of these
channels. This allows, for example, 16 different instruments to be playing
at once (each on a seperate channel).
@endnode

@node "UsingMIDIMaestro" "UsingĀMIDIMaestro"


                          @{"LoadingĀMIDIMaestro" link "Loading" 0}

                          @{"GettingĀon-lineĀhelp" link "Bubbles" 0}

                             @{"TheĀInputĀpage" link "InputPage" 0}

                            @{"TheĀOutputĀpage" link "OutputPage" 0}
@endnode

@node "Loading" "Loading MIDIMaestro"
@{b}@{u}Loading MIDIMaestro:@{ub}@{uu}

To load MIDIMaestro from the Workbench simply double click on its  icon. To
load from the CLI type:

MIDIMaestro <return>
@endnode

@node "Bubbles" "Getting on-line help"
@{b}@{u}Getting on-line help:@{ub}@{uu}

If it is not clear what a particular setting does then leave  the  mouse
pointer  over  the  setting  for  a  short period of time (set using @{"MUI" link "MUI" 0}
preferences) and a bubble help will appear describing that setting.  The
bubble  helps  are  only  provide  a short description. If you require a
detailed explanation then refer to this manual.
@endnode

@node "InputPage" "The Input page"
@{b}@{u}The Input page:@{ub}@{uu}

From this page the user can select between input from a file or  from  a
sampler.

If input is from a file then the file name should be  specified  in  the
"File Name" text entry. Any sound file format is supported that the user has
a @{"datatype" link "Datatype" 0} installed for. Clicking on button to the  right  of  this text
entry will  bring up a file requester to select an existing file. Once the
file has been selected the user can click  on  the  "play"  and "stop"
buttons to the right.

If input is from a sampler then the user must specify the  sample  rate. The
sample rate will determine the highest frequency of note that can be
detected (this is equal to half  the  sample  rate).  Note  that  higher
sample  rates take up much more processor time as there is more data to
process and less time to do it in. Therefore, always select  the  lowest
sample  rate possible for maximum performance. Simply drag the slider to set
the sample rate. The buffer size also  needs  to  be  set:  on  slow
machines  (less  than  030 processor  and no FPU) a large value will be
required (say 30.0 secs.) and on fast machines this can be much  smaller
(about  0.5 secs.). There is no harm in using large buffer sizes on fast
machibnes, however, it will just use more memory.  If  you  think  your
instrument may be out of tune (not tuned to concert pitch) then click on the
"Tuner" button to bring up a tuner.
@endnode

@node "OutputPage" "The Output page"
@{b}@{u}The Output Page@{ub}@{uu}

Clicking on the "Output" tab at the top of  the  window  will  show  the
Output  page.  This page control all options for output. It is sub-dived
into pages for selecting the destination(s) of the output (@{"Destination" link "DestinationPage" 0}),
setting MIDI  options (@{"MIDIĀOptions" link "MIDIOptionsPage" 0}), controlling the detection of @{"noteĀon" link "NoteOn" 0}
and @{"off" link "NoteOff" 0} messages (@{"NoteĀDetection" link "NoteDetectionPage" 0}), and settings for  controlling  the
detection of a note's pitch (@{"PitchĀDetection" link "PitchDetectionPage" 0}).


                            @{"Destination Page" link "DestinationPage" 0}

                           @{"MIDI Options Page" link "MIDIOptionsPage" 0}

                          @{"Note Detection Page" link "NoteDetectionPage" 0}

                          @{"Pitch Detection Page" link "PitchDetectionPage" 0}
@endnode

@node "Datatype" "datatype"
@{b}@{u}What is a datatype?@{ub}@{uu}

A datatype is something on the @{"Amiga" link "Amiga" 0} which allows programs to load lots of
different file formats. If the program does not support the file format you
want then you can install a new datatype for that format so that it does.
@endnode

@node "DestinationPage" "Destination"
@{b}@{u}The Destination Page:@{ub}@{uu}

This page is used to decide what forms of output will occur.  This  page is
further  sub-divided  into  pages  for  each of the possible outputs (@{"File" link "FilePage" 0},
@{"MIDIĀInterface" link "MIDIInterfacePage" 0}, and @{"Window" link "WindowPage" 0}). To enable output  to  any  of  these
destinations just select the checkmark (so that a tick appears) for the
required output. The options for each of these can then  be  changed  by
selecting  the appropriate sub-page.

Note: the options for a particular destination are greyed out if output  has
not  been  enabled  for  that destination.


                               @{"FileĀPage" link "FilePage" 0}

                          @{"MIDIĀInterfaceĀPage" link "MIDIInterfacePage" 0}

                              @{"WindowĀPage" link "WindowPage" 0}
@endnode

@node "MIDIOptionsPage" "MIDI Options"
@{b}@{u}MIDI Options Page@{ub}@{uu}

This page can be used to great effect for creating chords from each note
played on your instrument. It is possible to have a different instrument
playing each note of the chord and upto 16 notes in  the  chord.  Simply
select  which  @{"channels" link "Channels" 0}  you  want  notes  to be output on and set their
transpose value (the number of notes higher each channel will play above the
notes played on the instrument).
@endnode

@node "NoteDetectionPage" "Note Detection"
@{b}@{u}The Note Detection Page:@{ub}@{uu}

These options give control over the  detection  of  @{"NoteOn" link "NoteOn" 0}  and  @{"NoteOff" link "NoteOff" 0}
messages.

The following settings are available:

@{b}Attack Rate:@{ub}

This setting is used to identify a @{"NoteOn" link "NoteOn" 0} message.  The  attack is  the
sudden increase  in  volume when a note is played. If you find you play
notes and they were not detected then  try  again  after  lowering  this
value.  If,  on the  other  hand,  you  find it is detecting notes that
weren't played then increase this value.

@{b}Minimum Note Volume:@{ub}

This setting determines how loud a note has to be for a @{"NoteOn" link "NoteOn" 0} message to be
generated.If you find you play notes and they were not detected then try
again after lowering this value. If, on the other hand, you find  it is
detecting notes that weren't played then increase this value.

@{b}Note Off Volume:@{ub}

This setting is used to determine  when  a  @{"NoteOff" link "NoteOff" 0}  message should  be
generated.  If you find that notes are left to sustain for too long then
increase this value. If you find notes are  being  cut-off  too  quickly
then decrease this value.

@{b}Window Size:@{ub}

This setting is used to determine how frequently the volume of a note is
monitored.  If  you  find  that  none  of  the  above  settings give the
required effect then change this slightly and try  again.  A  value  of
about 20 millisecs. is sensiable.

@{b}Let Notes Ring:@{ub}

If you want notes to sustain forever, or until  the  MIDI device  stops
playing them, select this option (so a tick appears).

Some experimentation may be required to get reliable settings.  Remember
that output  can  be  sent  to a window to give some indication of what
settings may need adjusting.
@endnode

@node "PitchDetectionPage" "Pitch Detection"
@{b}@{u}Pitch Detection Page:@{ub}@{uu}

This page is used to control how the pitch of the note is determined.

Some experimentation  may  be  required  to  get  reliable  values.  The
following options are avilable:

@{b}Lowest Note:@{ub}

Set this to the frequency (in Hz) of the lowest note that is likely  to be
played on your instrument.

@{b}Missing Fundamental:@{ub}

Some low notes do not have a harmonic at the  fundamental frequency  of the
note.  This is generally only a problem with low notes. If you find that
when you play a low note the note found is an  octave  higher than the  one
played then  increase  this  value  so it is greater than the frequency of
that note and try again.

@{b}Higher Note Bias:@{ub}

This setting is used to decided between notes  which  are harmonics  of each
other.  A  high  value  will  bias  the decision towards a higher harmonic
whilst a low  value  will  bias  the  decision  towards  a low harmonic.  If
you find that sometimes a note lower than the note played is found then
increase this value. If you find that  a  higher  note  is sometimes found
then decrease this value.

@{b}Window Size:@{ub}

A high value here will increase the acuracy of the pitch detection  but take
longer  to  compute. Good results are still obtained even with its smallest
value of 100 millisecs.
@endnode

@node "FilePage" "File"
@{b}@{u}The File Page:@{ub}@{uu}

Here, options can be set for output  to  a  standard  MIDI  file.  These
options  are  all  self explanitory and are not required to be set for a
valid MIDI file to be generated (they are optional and  for  the  user's
benefit). Most transcribing software will use some of these setting when
displaying the musical notation.
@endnode

@node "MIDIInterfacePage" "MIDI Interface"
@{b}@{u}The MIDI Interface Page:@{ub}@{uu}

The MIDI Interface page allows the setting of a delay value after  which
MIDI messages  will  be  sent  to  the @{"MIDI interface" link "MIDIInterface" 0} for connection to
external MIDI equipment. On slower machines larger delay values will  be
required  in order  to  maintain the timing intervals between notes. On very
fast machines (68040 or 68060) this delay can  be  set  to  a  very small
value.
@endnode

@node "WindowPage" "Window"
@{b}@{u}The Window Page:@{ub}@{uu}

The Window page allow you to see all @{"MIDI" link "MIDI" 0} messages generated along  with
their parameters. This is useful for configuring the program to your own
instrument.

It is  possible  to  only  show  messages  for  particular  @{"channels" link "Channels" 0}  by
selecting the checkmark for the appropriate channel (so a tick appears). It
is also possible to  only  show  particular  messages  that  you  are
interested in  (e.g.  @{"NoteOn" link "NoteOn" 0}  messages)  by  selecting  the appropraite
checkmark in the Channels To Show section.
@endnode

